    <!-- Write-up (edit in VS Code) -->
   <section class="panel">
  <h2>Write-up</h2>
  </div>
  <p>This look draws from the Bauhaus movement — a place where art met function, and design became a language of shape, colour, and clarity. I’ve always been drawn to its balance of playfulness and precision — the idea that structure doesn’t have to be rigid, and simplicity doesn’t mean minimal thought.</p>
  <p>I wanted to explore how colour can exist as design, not decoration. Using sponges cut into geometric forms, I printed red, blue, and yellow directly onto the hair — a modern take on Bauhaus composition, built on instinct and balance rather than strict symmetry.</p>
  <p>The haircut itself was kept clean and sharp to let the colour lead — a stripped-back foundation that allowed the form and placement to speak. The result feels graphic yet wearable, abstract yet purposeful — like Bauhaus itself.</p>
  <p>It’s a reminder that concepts don’t need to be complicated to hold meaning. Sometimes the strongest ideas are the simplest ones — those that combine curiosity, craft, and clarity in equal measure.</p>
</section>


